I reviewed your code and it looks like the issue might be related to using a global list for the foodInstances that are shared among all TrainingArea instances. In order to make each TrainingArea independent, we need to create a separate list for each TrainingArea instance, so that they don't share the foodInstances list.

To do this, I suggest you make the following changes in your TrainingArea.cs script:

1. Change the static List<GameObject> foodInstances to not be static anymore:
```csharp
// Old code: private static List<GameObject> foodInstances = new List<GameObject>();
private List<GameObject> foodInstances = new List<GameObject>();
```

2. In the `ResetFoods` method, update the way you instantiate food to also set the parent to the current TrainingArea transform:
```csharp
// Old code: GameObject foodInstance = Instantiate(foodPrefab, spawnPosition, Quaternion.identity, transform);
GameObject foodInstance = Instantiate(foodPrefab, spawnPosition, Quaternion.identity, transform);
foodInstances.Add(foodInstance);
food.transform.SetParent(transform);
```

These changes should help ensure that each TrainingArea instance maintains its own foodInstances list, and their Player and Food objects don't interact with each other. This should eliminate the issues you described with food disappearing from the first agent and other players in the TrainingArea not being able to eat their own food.

I see. This is likely happening because the Physics2D.OverlapCircle check in your PlayerAgent.cs script is not considering the specific TrainingArea the player belongs to. It is casting the circle in global coordinates and detecting any food that it overlaps with, regardless of the TrainingArea it is part of. 

To solve this issue, you can make the following changes:

1. In TrainingArea.cs, add a new public method to get the current TrainingArea's foodInstances list:
```csharp
public List <GameObject> GetFoodInstances()
{
    return foodInstances;
}
```

2. In PlayerAgent.cs, update the OnActionReceived method to only consider food objects that are part of the PlayerAgent's TrainingArea:
```csharp
public override void OnActionReceived(ActionBuffers actions)
{
    float moveX = Mathf.Clamp(actions.ContinuousActions[0], -1, 1);
    float moveY = Mathf.Clamp(actions.ContinuousActions[1], -1, 1);

    Vector3 move = new Vector3(moveX, moveY, 0) * moveSpeed * Time.fixedDeltaTime;
    Vector3 newPosition = transform.localPosition + move;

    Collider2D collider = Physics2D.OverlapCircle(newPosition, 0.5f, LayerMask.GetMask("Wall"));
    if (collider == null || !collider.CompareTag("Wall"))
    {
        SetReward(-0.1f);
        transform.localPosition = newPosition;
    }

    Collider2D collider2 = Physics2D.OverlapCircle(newPosition, 0.5f, LayerMask.GetMask("Food"));
    if (collider2 != null && collider2.CompareTag("Food"))
    {
        // Make sure the food object is part of the current TrainingArea
        if (trainingArea.GetFoodInstances().Contains(collider2.gameObject)) 
        {
            Debug.Log("OnTriggerEnter2D");
            SetReward(1f);
            Destroy(collider2.gameObject);
        }
    }
}
```

This will make sure that the PlayerAgent only interacts with the food objects within its own TrainingArea, and it won't affect the food in other TrainingAreas.

