I see the issue. It's because the food instances are being instantiated and added to the list inside the foreach loop when resetting foods. When the episode starts, this loop resets food, but it may end up adding new food instances to the first TrainingArea due to the way the references are set. 

To fix this, modify the `ResetFoods` method in TrainingArea.cs like this:

```csharp
public void ResetFoods()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < foodInstances.Count; i++)
    {
        if (foodInstances[i] == null)
        {
            Vector3 spawnPosition = GetValidSpawnPosition();
            GameObject foodInstance = Instantiate(foodPrefab, spawnPosition + transform.position, Quaternion.identity, transform);
            foodInstances[i] = foodInstance;
        }
        else
        {
            foodInstances[i].transform.localPosition = GetValidSpawnPosition();
        }
    }
}
```

Here, we use a for loop instead of a foreach loop to iterate through the foodInstances list and directly replace the null elements with new food instances when needed. This should ensure that the new food appears in the corresponding TrainingArea.

Let me know if this resolves the issue.

